    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>An American Town Meeting: The Issue Is Race; The Sergeants</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Joseph Lucas letter, responding to June 7 article Which Man's Army?, in series How Race Is Lived in America, contends Army rotates troops in order to stir the mix and the black sergeant featured in article should not regard his transfer as racially motivated</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Which Man's Army'' (front page, June 7):</p>
        <p>While soldiers do develop loyalty to their units, they should not be carving out fiefs for themselves or members of their cliques (for example, blacks and whites).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Which Man's Army'' (front page, June 7):</p>
        <p>While soldiers do develop loyalty to their units, they should not be carving out fiefs for themselves or members of their cliques (for example, blacks and whites).</p>
        <p>The Army addressed the problem of fiefs long ago when it instituted rotation of troops, moving soldiers around every two to four years to stir the mix and keep soldiers on their toes. The black sergeant featured in your article who was transferred to another unit should not have viewed his reassignment as racially motivated.</p>
        <p>JOSEPH LUCAS  Cambridge, Mass., June 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
